or exploration would be acceptable to clarify this situation.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring serialization algorithms**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the serialization algorithm functions. It calls `writeSerialData` for each class from the highest in the hierarchy to the lowest. If a class has a `writeObjectData`, that’s used; otherwise, it defaults to `defaultWriteFields`. This means that the `Datum` fields get serialized by default. I'm unsure if `physicalConnection` in `DatumWithConnection` is transient or if the related variables are null. I need to check if `TestOracleConnection` is serializable and whether `OracleOCIConnection`, which extends `PhysicalConnection`, implements `Serializable`. It seems like running `javap` might help clarify this.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_p1ARqSQ7qn6H5vrvCy6m7Z4P|fc_034e2e4de9a0c5740169f7ea3acc7481a18f3943a619ca38b7", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/com.oracle.database.jdbc/ojdbc11/23.8.0.25.04/4d80d6fb56bbb5e20b3e3fa3183f2af13b533515/ojdbc11-23.8.0.25.04.jar oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleOCIConnection oracle.jdbc.driver.PhysicalConnection oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleConnection | grep -E 'class .*implements|class .*extends'", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1580, "output": 640, "cacheRead": 30208, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32428, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777855022780, "responseId": "resp_034e2e4de9a0c5740169f7ea2f45bc81a18997f5388dd49f46"}}
